feat: NTFS shrink relocation and resize-during-restore correctness

Make restoring to a smaller target actually work end-to-end. Previously
a shrink restore produced a RAW partition that chkdsk couldn't even
examine. The fix has two layers, both landed here:

Layer 1: resize-during-restore boot-sector patching
- NTFS, FAT(12/16/32), and exFAT now patch their respective size fields
  (BPB.TotalSectors, BPB_TotSecXX, VolumeLength + ClusterCount + boot
  checksum) so the on-disk filesystem agrees with the partition table
  the GPT layout step plants.
- partition_table.rs: split GPT init into CREATE_DISK then
  SET_DRIVE_LAYOUT_EX then UPDATE_PROPERTIES with the proper
  Anonymous.Gpt header populated; defer the layout/update phases until
  after data writes to avoid auto-mount races on ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED.
- raw.rs: PartitionWriter gained read_at + flush so the boot-sector
  patchers can do read-modify-write through the same handle that
  streamed the data.
- Restore now returns RestoreSummary { partitions_restored,
  partitions_resized }; CLI and GUI append a chkdsk /F hint when any
  partition was resized. GUI status text changed from "Restore in
  progress..." to "Preparing to restore, please wait..." to cover the
  pre-flight gap.

Layer 2: NTFS shrink relocation (Phase B of the plan)
- phoenix-cli inspect <backup.phnx> dumps each partition's stream
  header (extents + chunk table) for forensic investigation of
  manifest contents. Flags any extent whose values fall within 1 PiB
  of u64::MAX as suspicious.
- validate_extents_fit now logs the entire extent table at WARN level
  on overflow and embeds the first three offending extents in the
  error message.
- phoenix-core/relocation.rs holds the RelocationMap data type plus
  translate_cluster and translate_write segmentation logic.
- phoenix-restore/relocation.rs builds the map: identifies safe-zone
  free runs, greedy-packs above-boundary clusters into them, refuses
  with a precise byte-shortfall error when impossible.
- restore_raw learned an optional relocation parameter; chunks
  straddling the boundary split into multiple writes. NTFS shrink path
  in restore.rs builds the map up front and threads it through
  restore_ntfs to restore_raw and the metadata rewriter.
- phoenix-capture/ntfs_meta.rs walks every MFT record under the map:
  parses each non-resident attribute's run list, translates LCNs,
  re-encodes within the original byte budget (refuses if the encoding
  grew past it; v1 doesn't implement $ATTRIBUTE_LIST migration).
  Rewrites $Bitmap to clear past-boundary bits and set relocation
  destination bits; stamps $LogFile with 0xFF for clean-shutdown;
  copies the rewritten first 4 records to the MFT mirror; patches the
  boot sector's MftLcn / MftMirrLcn.
- validate_extents_fit's hard refusal for NTFS is replaced with a
  relocation-map build pre-flight; FAT/exFAT keeps the original
  refusal until shrink relocation lands for those filesystems.

Capture-side correctness fixes (Phase A of the plan) bundled in
because they sit in the same files:
- Fix three exFAT parse bugs in parse_fat_boot: cluster_size now uses
  BytesPerSectorShift + SectorsPerClusterShift (was BPS shift only,
  off by 8x), ClusterCount reads offset 92-95 (was 116-119, in
  Reserved), data_start uses ClusterHeapOffset * bytes_per_sector (was
  fat_offset + cluster_count * cluster_size, physically meaningless).
  Tighten exFAT magic check to full "EXFAT   " (was just byte[3]).
- Add fat_plan mirroring ntfs_plan; capture_fat and capture_exfat now
  consume planned extents from plan_capture instead of recomputing
  them internally. Fixes a latent extent-table-vs-chunk-index mismatch
  that would have panicked any non-trivial FAT/exFAT restore.

Tests:
- 6 new unit tests in phoenix-restore/relocation.rs covering map
  build, translation, and boundary splitting.
- 5 new unit tests in phoenix-capture/ntfs_meta.rs covering run-list
  parse/encode round-trips, sparse runs, relocation translation, and
  destination-discontinuity splitting.
